	#. In $#R#^2$, two distinct lines are either parallel (if they have the same slope) or they intersect. In $#R#^3$, there is another possibility: two distinct lines can be *parallel* if they have parallel direction vectors, *intersecting* if (of course) they intersect, and *skew* if neither of those is true. Determine whether each of these pairs of lines is parallel, intersecting, or skew.

	> a) $\left< -1 + 2t, 2 + 3t, 7t \right>$ and $\left< 3 - 6t, 1 - 9t, 10 - 21t \right>$.

	> b) $\left< 7 + 2t, -10 - t, 2 + t \right>$ and $\left< -8 + 3t, -3 - t, -9 + 5t \right>$.

	> c) $\left< 1 + t, 2 + t, 3 + t \right>$ and $\left< 4 + t, 5 - t, 7 + 2t \right>$.

	- - -

	#. Find a equation of a line passing through the points $(5, 1, 2)$ and $(3, 4, 1)$.

	#. Find an equation of the plane containing the points $(1, 0, 1)$, $(-3, 1, 1)$, and $(2, 4, 0)$.

	#. Find the intersection of the line from question #-2 and the plane from question #-1 if they exist, or show they don't intersect.

	#. Find three points in $#R#^3$ that have more than one plane passing through them. Given all of those planes, consider the set of unit normal vectors to them. What does that set look like?

